<A name=3DIntroduction></A>
<H2><SPAN class=3Dmw-headline>Introduction </SPAN></H2>
<DIV class=3D"thumb tleft">
<DIV class=3Dthumbinner style=3D"WIDTH: 182px"><A class=3Dimage=20
title=3D"Testing Environment"=20
href=3D"http://www.joshuajones.org/wiki/index.php?title=3DImage:Joy_scree=
n1.jpg"><IMG=20
class=3Dthumbimage height=3D100 alt=3D"Testing Environment"=20
src=3D"http://www.joshuajones.org/wiki/images/thumb/Joy_screen1.jpg/180px=
-Joy_screen1.jpg"=20
width=3D180 border=3D0></A>=20
<DIV class=3Dthumbcaption>
<DIV class=3Dmagnify style=3D"FLOAT: right"><A class=3Dinternal =
title=3DEnlarge=20
href=3D"http://www.joshuajones.org/wiki/index.php?title=3DImage:Joy_scree=
n1.jpg"><IMG=20
height=3D11 alt=3D""=20
src=3D"http://www.joshuajones.org/wiki/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.p=
ng"=20
width=3D15></A></DIV>Testing Environment</DIV></DIV></DIV>
<P>Just for fun, I thought I'd share how the new Xbox 360 controller =
interfaces=20
with DirectX via the Xinput interface. </P>
<P>To do this I'm using a sandbox program of mine codenamed "Crossbaby" =
for its=20
cross-platformness. One thing that computers have problems with in =
general is=20
dealing with any kind of joystick interface. This includes gamepads, =
joysticks,=20
steering wheels, etc. (I will call them "<I>joysticks</I>" from here =
out) There=20
are no standards in place so one joystick adapter can be totally =
different from=20
another. </P>
<P>I have 3 different PS2 adapters from 3 different companies. Each =
adapter=20
assigns the buttons, analog axies, etc., each a different way. So what's =
the big=20
deal? Well, that means that for every PC game I have I have to configure =
the=20
hell out of the joystick! Sometimes the game just doesn't care about =
some axis.=20
Halo PC has one of the best joystick configuration interfaces i've ever =
seen on=20
a computer. Wouldn't it be nice if we could just plug in a joystick and =
not have=20
to worry about it? </P>
<P>Now comes Microsoft with their almighty Xbox 360 controllers with USB =

interfaces. Compatable with PCs and Xbox 360s. I'm a big fan of great =
gamepads=20
so I thought i'd see what the big fuss is about. </P>
<DIV class=3Dcenter>
<DIV class=3D"thumb tnone">
<DIV class=3Dthumbinner style=3D"WIDTH: 182px"><A class=3Dimage=20
title=3D"Official Xbox 360 Controller"=20
href=3D"http://www.joshuajones.org/wiki/index.php?title=3DImage:Xbox360_c=
ontroller2.sized.jpg"><IMG=20
class=3Dthumbimage height=3D130 alt=3D"Official Xbox 360 Controller"=20
src=3D"http://www.joshuajones.org/wiki/images/thumb/Xbox360_controller2.s=
ized.jpg/180px-Xbox360_controller2.sized.jpg"=20
width=3D180 border=3D0></A>=20
<DIV class=3Dthumbcaption>
<DIV class=3Dmagnify style=3D"FLOAT: right"><A class=3Dinternal =
title=3DEnlarge=20
href=3D"http://www.joshuajones.org/wiki/index.php?title=3DImage:Xbox360_c=
ontroller2.sized.jpg"><IMG=20
height=3D11 alt=3D""=20
src=3D"http://www.joshuajones.org/wiki/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.p=
ng"=20
width=3D15></A></DIV>Official Xbox 360 =
Controller</DIV></DIV></DIV></DIV>
<P>The controller itself is very nice to hold. It has 4 axis for the =
left and=20
right thumbsticks, 2 axis for the left and right triggers, 10 buttons (4 =
colored=20
buttons, start, back, left &amp; right thumbsticks, and the left and =
right=20
shoulder buttons) The middle Xbox button can't be used with the official =
PC=20
driver, the indicator lights are used automatically. </P><A=20
name=3DImplementation></A>
<H2><SPAN class=3Dmw-headline>Implementation </SPAN></H2>
<P>Its going to take a few months for this to catch on to most big game =
titles=20
out there, but this controller can be used 2 different ways as far as =
DirectX is=20
concerned. I will refer to these two different interfaces as DirectInput =
and=20
Xinput. </P>
<P>99% of all Windows games that have joystick support use DirectInput. =
If you=20
were to plug the Xbox 360 controller into a computer without installing =
the=20
interface drivers it would be detected as a standard HID or Human =
Interface=20
Device. This is what DirectInput would use. Installing the official Xbox =
360=20
drivers adds the Xinput interface ability to the controller. </P>
<P>When you play a game on a console. There is nothing stopping you from =
just=20
removing the controller(s) from the system at any time. I dare you to =
try this=20
with any popular PC game out there. Basically the joystick has to be =
plugged in=20
before the game starts for the game to detect it. If you remove the =
joystick=20
while the game is running, the game will still work, but plugging the =
joystick=20
back in will not work. You have to usually close the game and reload it. =
How=20
annoying! </P>
<P>The Xinput interface allows you to plug and play during gameplay as =
if you=20
were playing on a console system. I'm pretty sure the interface on the =
Xbox 360=20
is almost identical to the interface on DirectX so it makes sense. =
</P><A=20
name=3DDifferences></A>
<H3><SPAN class=3Dmw-headline>Differences </SPAN></H3>
<DIV class=3Dcenter>
<DIV class=3D"thumb tnone">
<DIV class=3Dthumbinner style=3D"WIDTH: 182px"><A class=3Dimage=20
title=3D"Windows Control Panel Settings"=20
href=3D"http://www.joshuajones.org/wiki/index.php?title=3DImage:Xbox360co=
nfig.jpg"><IMG=20
class=3Dthumbimage height=3D171 alt=3D"Windows Control Panel Settings"=20
src=3D"http://www.joshuajones.org/wiki/images/thumb/Xbox360config.jpg/180=
px-Xbox360config.jpg"=20
width=3D180 border=3D0></A>=20
<DIV class=3Dthumbcaption>
<DIV class=3Dmagnify style=3D"FLOAT: right"><A class=3Dinternal =
title=3DEnlarge=20
href=3D"http://www.joshuajones.org/wiki/index.php?title=3DImage:Xbox360co=
nfig.jpg"><IMG=20
height=3D11 alt=3D""=20
src=3D"http://www.joshuajones.org/wiki/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.p=
ng"=20
width=3D15></A></DIV>Windows Control Panel =
Settings</DIV></DIV></DIV></DIV>
<P>One of the biggest differences I've noticed other than the whole plug =
and=20
play thing, is the trigger buttons. With DirectInput the left and right =
trigger=20
buttons share an axis. Its hard to visualize without seeing it in the =
Game=20
Controllers section of the Control Panel, but with no buttons being =
pressed the=20
axis is at 50%. With both buttons pressed down the axis is at 50%. =
Weird! </P>
<P>Xinput allows the left and right triggers to be treated separately. =
</P><A=20
name=3DMy_Implementation></A>
<H2><SPAN class=3Dmw-headline>My Implementation </SPAN></H2>
<P>DirectInput only detects 10 buttons on the controller, but I'd like =
to be=20
able to treat the left and right triggers as buttons as well, so I =
proclaim=20
there are 12 buttons now! DirectInput detects only 5 axis on the =
controller=20
since the left and right triggers share an axis in DirectInput land. I =
proclaim=20
6 axis! Take that subspace!&nbsp;:) </P><A name=3DHow_it_works></A>
<H2><SPAN class=3Dmw-headline>How it works </SPAN></H2>
<P>This is how it will work from the game player's perspective. You can =
start=20
the game with or without the controller plugged in; I chose to leave =
mine out=20
for this example. </P>
<DIV class=3Dcenter>
<DIV class=3D"thumb tnone">
<DIV class=3Dthumbinner style=3D"WIDTH: 182px"><A class=3Dimage=20
title=3D"Controller unplugged"=20
href=3D"http://www.joshuajones.org/wiki/index.php?title=3DImage:DSC00917.=
JPG"><IMG=20
class=3Dthumbimage height=3D135 alt=3D"Controller unplugged"=20
src=3D"http://www.joshuajones.org/wiki/images/thumb/DSC00917.JPG/180px-DS=
C00917.JPG"=20
width=3D180 border=3D0></A>=20
<DIV class=3Dthumbcaption>
<DIV class=3Dmagnify style=3D"FLOAT: right"><A class=3Dinternal =
